<TEI xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0" xmlns:frus="http://history.state.gov/frus/ns/1.0"><text><body><div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1919-07-23T15:00:00-05:00" frus:doc-dateTime-min="1919-07-23T15:00:00-05:00" n="296" subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d296">
                    <note rend="inline" type="source">Paris Peace Conf. 185.271/6: Telegram</note>
                    <head><hi rend="italic">The <gloss type="from">Commission to Negotiate
                                Peace</gloss> to the <gloss type="to">Acting Secretary of
                                State</gloss></hi></head>
                    <opener><dateline rendition="#right"><placeName><hi rend="smallcaps">Paris</hi></placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1919-07-23T21:00:00+01:00">July 23, 1919—9
                            p.m.</date></dateline></opener>
                    <p>3278. [From White.] In order to ascertain whether Colonel House expected to
                        return to Paris to sign the Austrian Treaty, I telegraphed him on July
                            19,<note n="71" xml:id="d296fn71">Telegram not printed.</note> at the
                        instance of the Drafting Committee who desired to know this definitely, in
                        connection with the preparation of the text. Colonel House has answered as
                        follows: <quote rend="blockquote">
                            <p>“The Commission on Mandates will sit in London August 5, therefore I
                                had better not undertake returning to Paris to sign the Treaty with
                                Austria.”</p>
                        </quote></p>
                    <closer><signed>White</signed><lb/><hi rend="smallcaps">Am</hi>[<hi rend="smallcaps">erican</hi>] <hi rend="smallcaps">Mission</hi></closer>
                </div>
                </body></text></TEI>